{"title_page": "Roberta Marrero", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name            = Roberta Marrero\n| image           =\n| alt             =\n| caption         =\n| birth_name      =\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1972|03|02|df=yes}}\n| birth_place     = [[Las Palmas]], Canary Islands, Spain\n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| death_cause     =\n| other_names     =\n| occupation      = Artist, singer, actress\n| years_active    =\n| known_for       =\n| notable_works   =\n| spouse          =\n| children        =\n| awards          =\n| alma_mater      =\n| website         =\n}}\n'''Roberta Marrero''' (born 2 March 1972) is a Spanish artist, singer, and actress.\n\n==Artistic career==\nIn her works as an illustrator, Roberta Marrero mixes and decontextualizes popular images, giving rise to new meanings, and using the technique of [[Appropriation (art)|artistic appropriation]]. For example, in her first published book, ''Dictadores'' (2015), she transforms several photographs of icons of [[totalitarianism]] with images related to the pop world. She thus shows [[Mao Zedong]] surrounded by characters whose faces have been covered by [[Hello Kitty]] heads, and presents a portrait of [[Francisco Franco]] made up with a lightning bolt on his face, in the style of [[David Bowie]] on the cover of ''[[Aladdin Sane]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2015/06/11/estilo/1434046196_424814.html |title=El dictador como fetiche pop |trans-title=The Dictator as Pop Fetish |first=Rafa |last=Cervera |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |location=Valencia |language=Spanish |date=12 June 2015 |access-date=29 May 2019}}</ref> With this publication, the artist stated that her intention was to \"Vandalize a fascist message and turn it into another one of freedom.\"<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=http://vein.es/roberta-marrero-no-una-artista-pop/ |title=Roberta Marrero: 'No soy una artista pop' |trans-title=Roberta Marrero: 'I am Not a Pop Artist' |first=Jaime |last=Mart\u00ednez |work=Vein |language=Spanish |date=25 July 2016 |access-date=29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn her 2016 book ''El beb\u00e9 verde: infancia, transexualidad y h\u00e9roes del pop'', a [[graphic novel]] with a prologue by the writer [[Virginie Despentes]], Marrero collects memories of her childhood and her [[transsexual]]ity, explaining how the worldview of various artists from pop music, literature, and cinema inspired her, especially [[Boy George]]. The main themes in her work are power, death, fame, love, and politics.\n\nIn addition to exhibiting in Spanish galleries such as \"La Fiambrera\" in Madrid, some of her works have been included in exhibitions such as ''[[David Bowie Is]]'', organized by the Victoria and Albert Museum in London,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.davidbowieis.es/en/bowie-cinema/ |title=Bowie Cinema |publisher=[[David Bowie Is]] |access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref> and ''Piaf'', at the [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]]. [[Joe Dallesandro]], model, actor and star of [[Andy Warhol]]'s [[The Factory]], chose one of her illustrations for limited edition t-shirts. Precisely, the author points to Warhol as her main influence. In addition, she samples from the [[Fauvism|Fauvist]] movement, [[expressionism]], [[surrealism]], [[Catholic art|Catholic religious painting]], [[Classical Hollywood cinema|classical Hollywood]], and [[Punk subculture|punk]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.yorokobu.es/roberta-marrero/ |title=Roberta Marrero: 'Warhol es la madre del punk' |trans-title=Roberta Marrero: 'Warhol is the Mother of Punk' |first=Mari\u00e1ngeles |last=Garc\u00eda |work=Yorokobu |language=Spanish |date=31 May 2016 |access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 Marrero denounced British fashion designer [[Vivienne Westwood]] on social media, claiming that one of her works had been plagiarized on a shirt sold through Westwood's website. The designer and her husband [[Andreas Kronthaler (fashion designer)|Andreas Kronthaler]] responded that the image had been copied without knowledge that it was a work by a contemporary artist.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2016/10/26/tentaciones/1477473746_215925.html |title=Vivienne Westwood copia un 'collage' de la artista espa\u00f1ola Roberta Marrero |trans-title=Vivienne Westwood Copies a 'Collage' from the Spanish Artist Roberta Marrero |first=Alberto |last=Sis\u00ed S\u00e1nchez |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |language=Spanish |date=26 October 2016 |access-date=29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs a musician, Marrero has released two [[electropop]] albums and has worked as a [[Disc jockey|DJ]] at several Spanish clubs.<ref name=Burton>{{Cite web |url=https://valenciaplaza.com/roberta-marrero-y-el-bebe-que-adoraria-tim-burton |title=Roberta Marrero y el beb\u00e9 que adorar\u00eda Tim Burton |trans-title=Roberta Marrero and the Baby Who Would Love Tim Burton |first=Rafa |last=Cervera |work=Valencia Plaza |location=Valencia |language=Spanish |date=25 December 2016 |access-date=29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n===Publications===\n* ''Dictadores'' (2015), Ediciones Hidroavi\u00f3n, {{ISBN|9788494414312}}\n* ''El beb\u00e9 verde: infancia, transexualidad y h\u00e9roes del pop'' (2016), Lunwerg Editores, {{ISBN|9788416489930}}\n* ''We Can Be Heroes. Una celebraci\u00f3n de la cultura LGTBQ+'' (2018), Lunwerg Editores, {{ISBN|9788416890743}}\n\n===Discography===\n* ''A la vanguardia del peligro'' (2005)\n* ''Claroscuro'' (2007)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://entrevistas.universogay.com/entrevista-a-roberta-marrero-cantante-y-actriz__29112007.html |title=Entrevista a Roberta Marrero, cantante y actriz |trans-title=Interview with Roberta Marrero, Singer and Actress |first=Rosi |last=Legido |work=Universo Gay |language=Spanish |date=29 November 2007 |access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Filmography===\n* ''Descong\u00e9late!'' (2003), directed by [[Dunia Ayaso and F\u00e9lix Sabroso]]<ref name=Burton/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Facebook}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marrero, Roberta}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Spanish actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Spanish women writers]]\n[[Category:Canarian actresses]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from Spain]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Spain]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Las Palmas]]\n[[Category:Spanish contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Spanish DJs]]\n[[Category:Spanish female singers]]\n[[Category:Spanish feminists]]\n[[Category:Spanish film actresses]]\n[[Category:Transgender and transsexual DJs]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language LGBT writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name            = Roberta Marrero\n| image           =\n| alt             =\n| caption         =\n| birth_name      =\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1972|03|02|df=yes}}\n| birth_place     = [[Las Palmas]], Canary Islands, Spain\n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| death_cause     =\n| other_names     =\n| occupation      = Artist, singer, actress\n| years_active    =\n| known_for       =\n| notable_works   =\n| spouse          =\n| children        =\n| awards          =\n| alma_mater      =\n| website         =\n}}\n'''Roberta Marrero''' (born 2 March 1972) is a Spanish artist, singer, and actress.\n\n==Artistic career==\nIn her works as an illustrator, Roberta Marrero mixes and decontextualizes popular images, giving rise to new meanings, and using the technique of [[Appropriation (art)|artistic appropriation]]. For example, in her first published book, ''Dictadores'' (2015), she transforms several photographs of icons of [[totalitarianism]] with images related to the pop world. She thus shows [[Mao Zedong]] surrounded by characters whose faces have been covered by [[Hello Kitty]] heads, and presents a portrait of [[Francisco Franco]] made up with a lightning bolt on his face, in the style of [[David Bowie]] on the cover of ''[[Aladdin Sane]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |u